				<h3> Scene 1 </h3>
				<img src="/images/aaliyahtalkstodoc.png" alt={`White Doctor`} class="float-img" />

				<p style="margin-left:50px" class=> Doctor: “Can you describe your symptoms to me?”</p>
				
				<p style="margin-left:50px" class=>
				Aaliyah: “Hello! I am 24 weeks pregnant right now. I haven’t been feeling myself lately, I’ve been more tired than usual, having frequent headaches, and I am concerned about me and my baby's health.”
				<br>
				<br>
				Doctor: “This is normal because your body is changing, a lot of people experience this. You will be fine, just get some rest.” 
				</p>	
				<p> Aaliyah goes home without receiving any proper care/diagnostics. </p>
				<p style="margin-top:0.5vh" class=><i>Aaliyah talks to her doctor</i></p>
			</div>
		</>
	)}

	{pageNumber === 6 && (
		<>
			<h2>Symptoms arise...</h2>
			<p>As days go by since her first visit to the doctor, Aaliyah starts to notice more complications arise. On top of frequent headaches, she develops blurry vision, abdominal pain, and worsening shortness of breath. </p>
			<img src="/images/pain.png" alt={`Symptoms arise.`} class="float-img" />
			<p><i>These symptoms are typically indicative of preeclampsia, a high blood pressure condition that can develop during pregnancy. This condition can affect other organs in your body such as the liver or the kidneys, which can put the mother and the fetus at risk. It is important that mothers with this condition can get treatment as soon as possible in order to avoid possible complications that could put their life at risk. (“Preeclampsia: Toxemia, Causes, Symptoms & Risk Factors”).</i> </p>
		</>
	)}
	
	{pageNumber === 7 && (
		<>
			<h2>Choose a doctor to take further care with...</h2>
			<div class="content">
				<p><a href={`/page/8`}>White Doctor</a></p>
				<p>OR</p>
				<p><a href={`/page/9`}>Black Doctor</a></p>
			</div>
		</>
	)}

	{pageNumber === 8 && (
		<>
			<h2>After visit with white doctor</h2>
			<div class="content">
				<img src="/images/whitedoc.png" alt={`Post-White doctor`} class="float-img" />
				<p>Aaliyah decides to call the doctor again, hoping the doctor would take her more seriously when she talks about the recurrence and worsening of the symptoms. </p>
				<p>Doctor: ”Hello, what seems to be the concern?”</p>
				<p>Aaliyah: ”Hi, my symptoms got worse. I’ve developed blurry vision, shortness of breath, abdominal pain.”</p>
				<p>Doctor: “Oh don’t worry, you just need to rest and take it easy. Your body is probably overreacting to all of the changes you are experiencing.”</p>
				<img src="/images/statpagewhite.png" alt={`Post-White doctor`} class="float-img" />
				<p>Unfortunately, just like Aaliyah, many Black women are often discriminated against during their healthcare visits, even more so than white women. There has been a larger amount of reports from Black women ages 18-64 of getting discriminated against during visits to a healthcare provider than White women, with that of Black women being 6% higher. (“Women's Experiences with Provider Communication and Interactions in Health Care Settings: Findings from the 2022 KFF Women's Health Survey”). </p>
				<p style="margin-top: 11vh;">One potential consequence is the death of the mother, especially with severe complications or disorders.</p>
				<p>Take a look at this image to the left, which shows us how many deaths there were per every 100,000 live births in 2022: </p>
